	doi = {10.1117/12.2314267},
	abstract = {A semi analytic framework for simulating the eﬀects of atmospheric seeing in Adaptive Optics systems on an 8-m telescope is developed with the intention of understanding the origin of the wind-butterﬂy, a characteristic twolobed halo in the PSF of AO imaging. Simulations show that errors in the compensated phase on the aperture due to servo-lag have preferential direction orthogonal to the direction of wind propagation which, when Fourier Transformed into the image plane, appear with their characteristic lemniscate shape along the wind direction. We develop a metric to quantify the eﬀect of this aberration with the fractional standard deviation in an annulus centered around the PSF, and use telescope pointing to correlate this eﬀect with data from an atmospheric models, the NOAA GFS. Our results show that the jet stream at altitudes of 100-200 hPa (equivalently 10-15 km above sea level) is highly correlated (13.2 ) with the strong butterﬂy, while the ground wind and other layers are more or less uncorrelated.},
